07620nam a22010455i 9780824884161DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248841617 a10.1515/97808248841612doi  a(DE-B1597)537287  a(OCoLC)1183956863  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0070002bisacsh04a294.3/37322300aBuddhism and Business :bMerit, Material Wealth, and Morality in the Global Market Economy /ced. by Trine Brox, Mark Michael Rowe, Elizabeth Williams-Oerberg. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Buddhism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor’s Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Buddhist Encounters with the Global Market Economy and Consumer Society -- t1 The Lama’s Shoes. Tibetan Perspectives on Monastic Wealth and Virtue -- t2 A Sino-Tibetan Buddhist Modernism. Religious Marketplace, Constellative Networking, and Urbanism -- t3 Prosperous Temple Buddhism and NRM Prosperity Buddhism -- t4 The Soka Gakkai Economy. Measuring Cycles of Exchange That Power Japan’s Largest Buddhist Lay Organization -- t5 The Mindful Gardener and the Good Employee. Mindfulness Practices and Affective Labor in Danish Workplaces -- t6 Branding and/as Religion. The Case of Buddhist-Related Images, Semantics, and Designs -- t7 Marketing the Buddha and Its Blasphemy -- t8 Economies of Religion, Buddhism and Economy, Buddhist Economics. Challenges and Perspectives -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough Buddhism is known for emphasizing the importance of detachment from materiality and money, in the last few decades Buddhists have become increasingly ensconced in the global market economy. The contributors to this volume address how Buddhists have become active participants in market dynamics in a global age, and how Buddhists and non-Buddhists alike engage Buddhism economically. Whether adopting market logics to promote the Buddha’s teachings, serving as a source of semantics and technologies to maximize company profits, or reacting against the marketing and branding of the religion, Buddhists in the twenty-first century are marked by a heightened engagement with capitalism.Eight case studies present new research on contemporary Buddhist economic dynamics with an emphasis on not only the economic dimensions of religion, but also the religious dimensions of economic relations. In a wide range of geographic settings from Asia to Europe and beyond, the studies examine institutional as well as individual actions and responses to Buddhist economic relations. The research in this volume illustrates Buddhism’s positioning in various ways—as a religion, spirituality, and non-religion; an identification, tradition, and culture; a source of values and morals; a world-view and way of life; a philosophy and science; even an economy, brand, and commodity. The work explores Buddhism’s flexible and shifting qualities within the context of capitalism, and consumer society’s reshaping of its portrayal and promotion in contemporary societies worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBuddhismxEconomic aspects. 0aEconomicsxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh1 aBorup, Jørn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorup, Jørn.1 aBrox, Trine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrox, Trine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrox, Trine.1 aCaple, Jane E.1 aCaple, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.